{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94206200-cdb2-4e81-99cf-8bbc92df5107","content":"Use **`dotnet-trace`** with the `System.Net.Http` EventSource provider. On .NET 8, this emits `RequestStart` (with URI) and `RequestStop` (with status code) events, giving you per-request timing and outcomes.\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Collect the trace (replace <PID> with your app's process ID)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> \\\n  --providers \"System.Net.Http:4:4\"\n```\n\nThe format is `Provider:Keywords:EventLevel` — `4:4` gives you **Informational** level events with the default keyword mask, which includes request start/stop with status codes.\n\n**To analyze**, open the resulting `.nettrace` file in:\n- **PerfView** (Windows) — filter to `System.Net.Http` events\n- **`dotnet-trace convert`** — export to Chromium or Speedscope format\n\n**What you'll see per request:**\n| Event | Fields |\n|-------|--------|\n| `RequestStart` | scheme, host, port, pathAndQuery |\n| `RequestStop` | statusCode |\n| `RequestFailed` | exceptionMessage (on hard failures) |\n\nTimestamps between Start/Stop give you duration.\n\n**Tip:** If you also want connection-level detail (DNS, TLS, socket reuse), add:\n\n```bash\n--providers \"System.Net.Http:4:4,System.Net.Security:4:4,System.Net.NameResolution:4:4\"\n```\n\nThis is non-invasive and doesn't require app restarts or code changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5637a9bd-bb2a-4332-896b-65335527270f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting traces/diagnostics for their .NET 8 ASP.NET Core app on Linux to diagnose intermittent HTTP 500 responses from a downstream API via HttpClient. They want to understand which requests are failing and how long they're taking.\n\nThis is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I should provide guidance on collecting the right traces.\n\nFor .NET on Linux, the key options are:\n\n1. **dotnet-trace** — collect EventPipe traces with the right providers\n2. **OpenTelemetry** — if already instrumented\n3. **HttpClient event sources** — specifically `System.Net.Http` EventSource\n\n\n4. **dotnet-trace** with `System.Net.Http` provider will capture the full lifecycle of each HttpClient request—from initiation through completion or failure—including the status codes, request URIs, and precise timing information needed to correlate failures with performance issues. Writing the trace command...","outputTokens":969,"requestId":"5021:35C209:1F4CFFF:23BF4AA:69F55268"},"id":"eae2ade8-4e1c-435c-b98d-db8c801793ce","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:25:15.923Z","parentId":"9129ac37-fa49-484d-aa8c-75f0427c3149"}
